reviewText:
A High Definition remake of the classic original, this and The Second Encounter are my favourite games of all time.
While this game, I'd say, is a bit behind TSE in terms of quality, I deem TFE to be a very good game nevertheless :
-the gunplay is rather solid;
-very fun 16 player Co-Op;
-the level design, while simplistic, often gives opportunities to look for resources and secrets and often isn't too restrictive;
-the esthetic I find to be quite nice and the music wonderfully fitting the game;
-the enemy variety for me is very adequate;

-and, the most importantly, I find the whole gameplay to be captivating. Serious Sam has a lot to do with knowing how to react to the different enemies, their movement, their attacks. And because of the large enemy variety, one not only has to decide what enemy is the most dangerous at that given time and which weapon suits that particular situation the most, one also has to move in such precise ways so that he escaped all those different projectiles and melee attacks, at the same time being aware of his surroundings - this could be called 'Dancing with the enemies' : constantly and precisely moving, jumping and shooting amidst enemies, rockets and whatever the game throws at you. It requires skill, decision making and just general knowledge of the game- so Serious Sam is not a mindless shooter, contrary to the popular belief.

Talking about The Second Encounter, it does so many things so well :
-the pacing of the campaign is very fast;
-extensive, varied and beautiful enviroments with a lot of secrets/resources;
-once again, a wonderful soundtrack that fits the game perfectly;
-more weapons compared to TFE, yet most guns are still very useful;
-loads of new well-designed enemies to tare apart with your SBC Cannon (The Mighty Cannon FTW!);
-even bigger enemy variety than its predecessor - to the extent where it's probably the best I've seen in a shooter.
-even better at that whole 'Dancing with the enemies' thing, making the game even more interesting and challenging.

Seriously, what else can you ask from a shooter?
